<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width="95%"><TR><td bgcolor="#F7F7F7"><TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="100%"><TR bgcolor="#9FA6C4"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#000000" FACE="Verdana">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#E8EAF0"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Soloer</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">According to Verant, some race/class combos can be soloed effectively. Can someone please tell me which ones they are? I like to play in groups, but as this is not always possible, I'd also like to be able to play alone effectively. (I've posted this message under those classes that I think are possibilities).<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#D9DCE8"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Kilborne</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Actually I think Verant said something to the effect that any class could be soloed to lvl 50, but at some point it would cease being fun and start to become hard work.<BR>Any class is 'fairly' easy to get to lvl 20, after that things get hard.  The classes that are easy to solo after level 20 (IMO) right now are druids (kiting) and necros (nice pets).  HOWEVER, on the test server they are implementing changes to 'nerf' both these classes.  There is coding (again on the test server) which prohibits DOT spells from taking affect if a MOB is running toward the caster, effectively destroying kiting as a tactic.  Also the strength of the necro pets has been severally downgraded.<BR>I support both these changes.  Kiting is a cheap tactic that allows druids (to a lesser extent shamans) to solo red cons all day and level pretty darn fast.  And the necro pets are REALLY strong right now.  I grouped with an equal level necro the other day and his naked unarmed pet out-fought me.  Not only that, but the pet heals back to full in about 5 seconds after combat.  How fair is that?<BR>It remains to be seen if Verant brings these on to the mainstream servers, but they do seem to be adjusting two of the most powerful (and easily soloable) classes back into the fold so to speak.<P>Kilborne<BR>Half-Elven Paladin of Marr<BR>23rd circle</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#E8EAF0"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Jaff</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Verant, for some godforsaken reason, HATES soloists. I, of course, hate them for this and do it whenever possible just to make them mad } <IMG SRC="http://www.everlore.com/boards/EL/smile.gif"> If any class is found to solo effectively (for instance, the paladins of the Beta in the days of yore) then they "Nerf" these classes so that they are forced to group. While kiting red cons as a druid isn't fair, the whole point of a DoT spell IS kiting. If you don't use DoT's to kite, then what the heck is the point of the DoT!? It's just a less practical DD spell. Whatever, back to soloing.<BR> It's true that after level 20, the average garden variety high-green con can easily wipe you off the map. Strange...I thought I'd get stonger as I gained levels...</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#D9DCE8"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Kilborne</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Well you can argue the solo/anitsolo thing all day.  It used to annoy me that it became all but impossible to solo my beloved paladin , but after making some friends online and spending some time in particular dungeons I find it easy to get a group and am having a great time.  <BR>As for DOTs I totally disagree.  The point of DOTs is not to kite it is to do massive damage for little mana.  DOTs often do 2 times (or more) the damage per mana that DD spells do.  The downside is that it may take a full minute to do this damage.  Anyway kiting is a cheap tactic (bordering on cheating) that simply takes advantage of the MOBs lack of real intelligence.     <P>------------------<BR>Sir Kilborne Halidar<BR>Paladin of Marr<BR>26th circle<BR>Bristlebane</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE></td></tr></table> 
